**Version Used**: master

**Steps to Reproduce**:

Consider the following program:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class C
{
    public async Task M(ArrayWrapper<S> array)
    {
        array[0].x = await Task.FromResult(1);
    }
}

public class ArrayWrapper<T>
{
    public ArrayWrapper(T[] array) => _array = array;
    T[] _array;
    public ref T this[int index] => ref _array[index];
}

public struct S
{
    public int x;
}
```

The correct semantics for `M` is 

```csharp
    public async Task M(ArrayWrapper<S> array)
    {
        ref var temp = array[0];
        var temp_result = await Task.FromResult(1);
        temp.x = temp_result;
    }
```

However this is impossible to code gen since a ref cannot survive across an await.

On @CyrusNajmabadi version of Roslyn (3.6.0-1.20127.6 (572b1f0e)) there's an error:

`error CS8178: 'await' cannot be used in an expression containing a call to 'ArrayWrapper<S>.this[int].get' because it returns by reference`

However in Sharplab on all branches it compiles with the following code gen:

```csharp
    public async Task M(ArrayWrapper<S> array)
    {
        var temp_result = await Task.FromResult(1);
        array[0].x =  temp_result;
    }
```

This breaks LTR semantics, since `Task.CompletedTask` is evaluated before the index access, i.e. even if an IndexOutOfRangeException is thrown.

So three questions:

1. Why do the compilers disagree?
2. Is this legal?
3. If so what should the code gen be?

Note this issue is similar to https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/issues/42464

However that is a simpler bug to fix since there is a valid codegen for an array index:

Namely:
```csharp
    public async Task M(S[] array)
    {
        array[0].x = await Task.FromResult(1);
    }
```
is compiled down to:

```csharp
    public async Task M(S[] array)
    {
        var arrayTemp = array;
        var indexTemp = 0;
         var dummyAccess = arrayTemp[indexTemp];
         var resultTemp= await Task.FromResult(1);
         arrayTemp[indexTemp].x = resultTemp;
    }
```

This is allowed since an array index on the same array with the same index is guaranteed to be idempotent. That is not the case with custom indexers/properties.

